<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{koto}}</strong> represents an intangible thing.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ii<strong>koto</strong>wo@KJ{{teach}}eteagemashou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'll tell you a good thing./I have a good suggestion for you.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{argument^sentence}}ni@KJ{{write}}ta<strong>koto</strong>wo@KJ{{tale}}shitekudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please tell me what you wrote in your thesis.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{koto}}</strong> can only be used to refer to something intangible. For tangible items use
<a href="grammar-mono-da.html">@HI{{mono}}</a>.
</p>

<p>
@N{{}}@HI{{no<strong>koto</strong>}} is often used with verbs such as @HI{{shitteiru}}, @KJ{{tale}}@HI{{su}} 
and @KJ{{part}}@HI{{karu}} to mean !about @N{{}}".
</p>

